node.text: It isn’t easy to defend our planet from asteroids. That’s why we support those who step up to the job.

Star Trek: Voyager's holographic doctor, Robert Picardo, also serves on The Planetary Society Board of Directors. However, he is not the first connection between Star Trek and The Planetary Society. In 1980, the creator of Star Trek, Gene Roddenberry, wrote a letter and sent it out to a Star Trek fans mailing list. In the letter, Gene invited his fans to join us on our mission to explore the cosmos.

Hear the letter as read by Robert Picardo, listen to his Jean-Luc Picard impression, and see inside Bill Nye's office for more Star Trek artifacts on hand at The Planetary Society.

Read the full letter at planetary.org

node.text: We can now sail on sunlight in space, just like a sailboat at sea! Our CEO @BillNye explains how.

node.title: Bill Nye explains: A new way to travel space

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by The Planetary Society on September 18, 2021.

node.text:
That feeling when things turn out better than expected.

LightSail 2 completed its primary mission and is now on an extended mission dedicated to further advancing solar sailing technology.

We're continuing to make changes to our sail control software, which will help future solar sail missions optimize their performance. We also plan to test using the sail to intentionally generate additional atmospheric drag, which is a way in which future spacecraft could deorbit themselves, cutting down on the ever-growing amount of space debris.

This LightSail 2 image, taken on June 8, 2020, shows Botswana, Zambia, Angola, Namibia, and Zimbabwe. The dark feature in the lower left is the Okavango Delta.

Has LightSail 2 inspired you?

#space #light #science

node.text:
Astronauts aboard the International Space Station have free time that they can spend as they choose. One of the most popular activities is simply looking down at the Earth, soaking up rare and spectacular views from above.

Our planet shines with orange light in this image taken by an astronaut aboard the International Space Station in 2018. This is airglow, a phenomenon that happens in planetary atmospheres. Radiation from the Sun strikes and energizes molecules in the atmosphere, which causes them to release energy that we can see as colors — most commonly red, green or blue, and in this case orange.

What are your favorite kinds of ISS images?

(📸 : NASA)

#space #science #stars

node.text:
There are between 100 billion and 1 trillion stars in our Milky Way galaxy.

If you counted one number a second from the time you were born until you hit one billion, you would be 31.7 years old by the time you finished. That's over 30,000 years to get to a trillion.

Think about that the next time you look up at the night sky. It's humbling and beautiful.

(📸 : NASA)

#space #milkyway #stars

The mirror @nasa's upcoming James Webb Space Telescope has a diameter of 6.6 meters (about 22 feet), more than 2.5 times wider than Hubble's. We can't wait for JWST's first images.

This graphic shows a comparison of the mirror sizes for the Spitzer, Hubble, and Webb telescopes.

What's the largest telescope you've seen in person?

(📸 : NASA/ESA/STScI/The Planetary Society)

Enceladus, a moon of Saturn, is spewing geysers into space, and we want to know more about what's in them!

Leadership, hope, generosity and prosperity are joining forces to venture into space. Today, @SpaceX's Inspiration4, the first all-civilian crew, launches into orbit.

Inspiration4 is meant to inspire everyday people to dream of a future where space is accessible to everyone. The crew members were chosen based on their inspirational life stories. The mission hopes to raise $200 million in donations for St. Jude Children's Hospital.

Inspiration4's 24-hour launch window opens at 8 pm EDT (midnight UTC).

South Korea is just a year away from launching its first Moon mission!

The Korean Pathfinder Lunar Orbiter, or KPLO, will study the Moon's surface and help us plan future missions to the lunar poles.

One of KPLO's instruments is called the ShadowCam, which can see inside permanently shadowed craters on the Moon. These regions may host water ice that will be important for future lunar exploration.

How long do you think it will be before humans have a permanent lunar settlement?

This artist’s impression of the Korean Pathfinder Lunar Orbiter shows the spacecraft mapping a permanently shadowed region on the Moon. 

(🖼️ : KARI)

node.text:
In 2019, our crowdfunded LightSail 2 mission was named one of @time's 100 best inventions of the year. Good times.

What are your favorite space exploration technologies?

This image taken by LightSail 2 on January 21, 2020 includes the west coast of India. North is at right. The sail appears slightly curved due to the spacecraft's 185-degree fisheye camera lens. The image has been color corrected and some of the distortion has been removed.

#space #inventions #science

node.text:
There are billions and billions of exoplanets in our galaxy, so — where are the aliens?

The Drake equation estimates the number of intelligent civilizations in our galaxy that are currently transmitting signals. It depends on seven factors:

- the yearly formation rate of stars hospitable to planets where life could develop
- the fraction of those stars with planets
- the number of planets per solar system with conditions suitable for life
- the fraction of planets suitable for life on which life actually appears
- the fraction of planets with life on which intelligent life emerges
- the fraction of planets with intelligent life that develops technologies such as radio transmissions that we could detect
- the average length of time in years that civilizations produce such signs

Which of these factors do you think is most interesting?

@nasa’s Hubble Space Telescope captured the images used to create this composite of globular cluster NGC 6397 in 2004 and 2005. Located 7,800 light-years from Earth, the cluster contains hundreds of thousands of ancient stars.

(📸 : NASA, ESA, Tom M. Brown (STScI), Stefano Casertano (STScI), Jay Anderson (STScI))

In 2004, @nasa announced that the final servicing mission to @nasahubble was canceled. Planetary Society members and space fans around the world sent letters to the US Congress to advocate for the beloved telescope, and it worked! 🎉

How have Hubble images impacted you?

Second Martian rock sample achieved!

NASA's Perseverance rover successfully processed and stored another rock core for later study on Earth. That's the second Martian sample collected this week (or ever). Quite an accomplishment!

These images taken by Perseverance show the holes made in the rock during sampling and the new rock core inside the sample tube.

What do you hope we will learn from these samples?

(📸 : NASA/JPL-Caltech/ASU/MSSS)
